Biblioteca

Target IP: 10.10.23.251

Scanning


There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 8000: HTTP

The web-page above is displayed for this application. Creating a new user account and signing in does not reveal anything useful.


However, I performed SQL injection to bypass the login by using the payload admin' OR '1'='1'-- // for username. There is an interesting username called smokey.

Exploitation


I ran hydra with the command hydra -l smokey -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt ssh://10.10.23.251 -t 4
to bruteforce the SSH password of the user smokey. While waiting, I decided to enumerate the web application further. I intercepted the POST request in a file, saved it as req.txt, and used sqlmap for futher investigation. Using sqlmap with the command sqlmap -r /home/kali/Desktop/Lab-Resource/Revisit/Biblioteca/req.txt --dump, I dumped the password of the web-application users, as shown above. Now I have the password of the user smokey.


Spraying the credential I obtained from the database dump against SSH, I gained access as smokey. Now I have a foothold on the machine.

Privilege Escalation & Flags


Since this task mentions "weak password". I tried hazel:hazel and it worked.


Looks like /usr/bin/python3 /home/hazel/hasher.py can be used for PE. It also has a SETENV.


I created a copy of the hashlib module inside /tmp directory. This copy contains a Python reverse shell script, to point to my machine, at the beginning.


Then I ran the binary using the command above.


On my machine at port 8444, I received a root shell from the target machine. The flags are shown above.
